# Deploy workflow: laptop first, server second

Always change and verify on the **local laptop project** (`c:\Users\n.fathi\projects\taskhub`) before touching production.

## Order of operations

1. **Local** — implement, test, and (when asked) commit/push from the laptop repo.
2. **Server** — only after local changes are ready, update production at `taskhub.modalalco.com`.

Never patch production directly without the same change existing locally first.

## Production server

- Host: `taskhub.modalalco.com`
- SSH user: `taskhub`
- App path: `/home/taskhub/taskhub`
- Stack: Docker Compose (`backend`, `caddy`, `postgres`, `redis`, `frontend-build`)

## Typical server update (after push)

```bash
cd ~/taskhub
git pull
docker compose up -d --build
```

Rebuild only what changed when possible:

- Backend API/routes/services: `docker compose up -d --build backend`
- Frontend UI: `docker compose up -d --build frontend-build` (then restart `caddy` if needed)

After deploy, verify critical endpoints (e.g. `GET /api/health`, `GET /api/projects` returns 401 not 404).

## Reminders

- Frontend and backend must both be rebuilt when their code changes; rebuilding one alone can leave the app broken.
- Do not commit secrets (`.env`, passwords) from the server into git.
